And so the subtle matter strikes incessantly the parts of the rigid body, and its particles which are almost infinite in number and distributed through the whole mass of the rigid body all cooperate to restore to their original shape the pores of the rigid body and conse· quently the rigid body itself. And in this effort the explanation of elasticity seems to lie.

For although the string itself may be a loose body, yet its minute fibres are somewhat rigid and their shapc alters with the extension of the string. But the move- ment of the contracting string is caused by the eflort of its fibres to revert to their original form.
